---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
const url = (path: string) => `${base}${path}/`;

const oxaExample = `{
  "type": "Claim",
  "identifier": "hypothesis-distinct-compartmental-roles",
  "role": "hypothesis",
  "epistemicStrength": "moderate",
  "children": [{
    "type": "Text",
    "value": "Perisomatic and distal dendritic inhibition serve
      distinct computational roles in regulating
      neuronal output."
  }],
  "relations": [
    { "xref": "prediction-distal-dendritic-spike-mechanism",
      "relationType": "claimrel:entails" },
    { "xref": "prediction-beta-optimal-distal",
      "relationType": "claimrel:entails" }
  ]
}`;

const dgExample = `{
  "@id": ".../hypothesis-distinct-compartmental-roles",
  "@type": "dg:Claim",
  "dg:content": "Perisomatic and distal dendritic
    inhibition serve distinct computational roles
    in regulating neuronal output.",
  "dg:role": "hypothesis"
}`;
---

<Layout title="Standards alignment">
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-16">

    <div class="mb-12">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 tracking-tight mb-3">Standards alignment</h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mb-6">How claim-level structure connects to the open scientific publishing ecosystem</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Reasoning -->
    <div class="mb-12 max-w-3xl space-y-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        A claim graph is only as useful as the systems that can consume it. If claims are locked in a custom format, they reach the tools we build and nothing else. If they speak the same language as the standards the ecosystem is converging on, they become part of the infrastructure.
      </p>
      <p>
        Three standards matter here. <strong>OXA</strong> (Open Exchange Architecture) is the emerging shared schema for scientific documents — backed by Curvenote, Stencila, eLife, and others. <strong>CiTO</strong> (Citation Typing Ontology) is the most widely adopted vocabulary for typed citation relationships. <strong>Discourse Graphs</strong> defines an ontology for structured scientific knowledge (Question / Claim / Evidence / Source) with formal OWL semantics.
      </p>
      <p>
        We adopt OXA as the native format for claims, use CiTO for edge types where it covers our needs, extend CiTO with 8 subproperties for claim-specific relationships it lacks, and produce Discourse Graphs JSON-LD as an interoperability export. The result: claims from this corpus can be consumed by any OXA-aware tool, queried via standard CiTO SPARQL, and integrated into Discourse Graphs knowledge bases.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- OXA -->
    <div class="mb-14">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-1">OXA — native format</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mb-4">
        <a href="https://oxa.dev" class="hover:underline" target="_blank">oxa.dev</a> — Open Exchange Architecture, CC-BY-4.0
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Each claim is an OXA node: a typed JSON object with inline content (the proposition), a role, panel anchors, and typed relations to other claims. The structure follows OXA's RFC patterns — the same node model used for headings, paragraphs, images, and citations. We are drafting an OXA RFC to propose <code>Claim</code> as a first-class node type in the specification.
      </p>
      <pre class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50 border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 text-xs text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 overflow-x-auto leading-relaxed mb-3"><code>{oxaExample}</code></pre>
      <a href="/elife-claim-trees/exports/headley.oxa.json" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-sm text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400 hover:underline" target="_blank">
        Download: Headley 2026, full paper in OXA format (26 claims) &rarr;
      </a>
    </div>

    <!-- CiTO + extensions -->
    <div class="mb-14">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-1">CiTO — edge vocabulary</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mb-4">
        <a href="https://sparontologies.github.io/cito/current/cito.html" class="hover:underline" target="_blank">SPAR Ontologies</a> — Citation Typing Ontology, CC-BY-4.0
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        CiTO defines 40+ typed citation relationships. Six of our 14 edge types map directly to CiTO properties.
        The remaining eight are defined as CiTO subproperties in a claim-relations vocabulary — preserving entailment
        so that any SPARQL query for <code>cito:cites</code> also retrieves our edges.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The gap is telling: CiTO covers the <em>social</em> relations between papers (agrees, disagrees, credits, reviews)
        but misses the <em>logical</em> relations within arguments (requires, tests, entails, scopes). Those five missing types
        are exactly what makes a claim graph different from a citation graph.
      </p>

      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-x-8 gap-y-0.5 text-sm mb-4">
        <div class="py-1.5 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">
          <code class="text-xs bg-green-50 dark:bg-green-900/20 text-green-800 dark:text-green-300 px-1 py-0.5 rounded">cito</code>
          <strong class="ml-1">supports</strong> · <strong>extends</strong> · <strong>qualifies</strong>
        </div>
        <div class="py-1.5 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">
          <code class="text-xs bg-green-50 dark:bg-green-900/20 text-green-800 dark:text-green-300 px-1 py-0.5 rounded">cito</code>
          <strong class="ml-1">disagreesWith</strong> · <strong>usesMethodIn</strong> · <strong>citesAsSourceDocument</strong>
        </div>
        <div class="py-1.5 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">
          <code class="text-xs bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 px-1 py-0.5 rounded">ext</code>
          <strong class="ml-1">tests</strong> · <strong>entails</strong> · <strong>requires</strong> · <strong>scopes</strong>
        </div>
        <div class="py-1.5 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">
          <code class="text-xs bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 px-1 py-0.5 rounded">ext</code>
          <strong class="ml-1">interprets</strong> · <strong>rulesOut</strong> · <strong>replicates</strong> · <strong>contradicts</strong>
        </div>
      </div>
      <a href="/elife-claim-trees/exports/claim-relations.ttl" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-sm text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400 hover:underline" target="_blank">
        Download: claim-relations.ttl (OWL vocabulary) &rarr;
      </a>
    </div>

    <!-- Discourse Graphs -->
    <div class="mb-14">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-1">Discourse Graphs — interoperability export</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mb-4">
        <a href="https://discoursegraphs.com" class="hover:underline" target="_blank">discoursegraphs.com</a> — Joel Chan, University of Maryland
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Discourse Graphs defines a four-type ontology for scientific knowledge: Question, Claim, Evidence, Source. Our claims map to this ontology: hypotheses and predictions become DG Claims, empirical results become DG Evidence, literature-context claims become DG Sources. The JSON-LD export makes our corpus queryable by any tool that speaks the DG ontology.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The mapping is lossy in one direction — DG's relation vocabulary (supports / opposes / addresses / interpretedAs) is smaller than ours. We carry the original CiTO relation type alongside the DG mapping so no information is lost.
      </p>
      <pre class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50 border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 text-xs text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 overflow-x-auto leading-relaxed mb-3"><code>{dgExample}</code></pre>
      <a href="/elife-claim-trees/exports/headley.dg.jsonld" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-sm text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400 hover:underline" target="_blank">
        Download: Headley 2026, Discourse Graphs JSON-LD &rarr;
      </a>
    </div>

    <!-- Claim roles reference -->
    <div class="mb-14">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-3">The 9 claim roles</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Every claim carries a <strong>role</strong> — its rhetorical function in the paper's argument.
        This vocabulary extends Stencila's existing Claim types (which cover formal/mathematical claims like theorems and proofs) into empirical science.
      </p>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-3 text-sm">
        <div class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-3">
          <div class="font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">hypothesis</div>
          <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-0.5">The paper's central bet — often implicit</div>
        </div>
        <div class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-3">
          <div class="font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">prediction</div>
          <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-0.5">Testable consequence of a hypothesis</div>
        </div>
        <div class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-3">
          <div class="font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">empirical</div>
          <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-0.5">Measured result, panel-grounded</div>
        </div>
        <div class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-3">
          <div class="font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">control</div>
          <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-0.5">Rules out an alternative explanation</div>
        </div>
        <div class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-3">
          <div class="font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">scope</div>
          <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-0.5">Boundary condition on other claims</div>
        </div>
        <div class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-3">
          <div class="font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">methodological</div>
          <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-0.5">Capability of the apparatus</div>
        </div>
        <div class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-3">
          <div class="font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">synthesis</div>
          <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-0.5">Integrates multiple results</div>
        </div>
        <div class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-3">
          <div class="font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">interpretation</div>
          <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-0.5">Reframes through theory</div>
        </div>
        <div class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-3">
          <div class="font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">literature-context</div>
          <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-0.5">Cited prior result</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Corpus stats -->
    <div class="mb-14">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-3">The corpus in standards-aligned format</h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-4">
        <div class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50 rounded-xl p-5">
          <div class="text-3xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">231</div>
          <div class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">claims</div>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50 rounded-xl p-5">
          <div class="text-3xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">503</div>
          <div class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">typed relations</div>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50 rounded-xl p-5">
          <div class="text-3xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">10</div>
          <div class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">eLife papers</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">
        All 10 eLife papers in the curated corpus, expressed as OXA-native JSON with CiTO-mapped edges. All 9 roles and 14 edge types represented.
      </p>
    </div>

  </div>
</Layout>
